    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Early 20th-century eugenicists primarily relied on pseudo-scientific theories to justify racial hierarchies. They claimed that certain racial groups, particularly those with lighter skin and European features, possessed superior intelligence, moral character, and physical abilities, while others, such as people of color and those with perceived \"undesirable\" traits, were deemed inferior. They also pointed to supposed genetic differences in skin color, cranial structure, and other physical characteristics as evidence of inherent racial superiority. Furthermore, eugenicists often invoked the idea of \"racial purity\" and the need to prevent \"miscegenation\" to preserve the supposed genetic integrity of dominant racial groups.",
